Environmental Change Network · UK Bird Monitoring

How did UK bird populations change over time?

Real data from 7 places across the UK, collected by scientists every year for decades. Scroll to discover which birds increased, which decreased — and which stayed the same.

What is a nesting group?

Scientists walk fixed routes through each site every year and count how many pairs of each bird species they find nesting. Each pair is called a nesting group. More nesting groups means more breeding pairs were recorded at that site.

7 sites · up to 33 years of data · 1971–2007

What does it all mean?

Across UK’s farms, grasslands and woodlands, some species were recorded more often over time while others were recorded less. These charts show how total nesting groups across all recorded species changed at each site.

Sites were monitored at different times and for different lengths, so totals aren’t directly comparable between sites — but the patterns in the recorded counts at each site are real.
